In Lean 4, `ctble U` is defined as `∃ f : U → Nat, Function.Injective f`. So a one-to-one function `f` gives us the injective function needed for the definition of countable.

So for the forward direction: `ctble U → ∃ f, one_to_one f`.

If `ctble U` holds, then there exists an injective function `f : U → Nat`. An injective function is one-to-one, so we can take this `f` as our witness.

For the reverse direction: `∃ f, one_to_one f → ctble U`.

If there exists a one-to-one function `f : U → Nat`, then `f` is injective. The existence of an injective function from `U` to `Nat` is equivalent to `U` being countable. So we can use this `f` to satisfy the definition of countable.

